-- ── CloudBees ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$CloudBees is an enterprise CI/CD and software delivery platform, historically the primary commercial company behind the Jenkins open-source automation server, now built around a newer product called CloudBees Unify that adds AI-assisted pipeline intelligence, release orchestration, and security posture management on top of existing tools including Jenkins and Kubernetes. Founded in 2010 by Sacha Labourey and Francois Dechery, the company is headquartered in San Jose, California. In September 2025, CloudBees carried out layoffs affecting about 12 percent of its workforce while continuing to raise growth financing, including a $150 million Series F round and a $95 million debt facility at a $1 billion valuation.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Primarily custom, quote-based subscription pricing negotiated per organization, with a reported free tier for small teams and seat-based team pricing for CloudBees Unify$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free tier reported for up to 5 users; paid team and enterprise pricing is custom-quoted$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2010, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$500-600 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Jose, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CloudBees Review 2026: CI/CD Pricing and Jenkins Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CloudBees review: pricing, CloudBees Unify features, Jenkins heritage, and 2025-2026 company news for this enterprise CI/CD and DevOps platform.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CloudBees is an enterprise software delivery and CI/CD company founded in 2010 by Sacha Labourey and Francois Dechery, headquartered in San Jose, California, with additional offices including Raleigh, North Carolina; Lewes, Delaware; Richmond, Virginia; Berlin; London; and Neuchatel, Switzerland. The company built its early business as the primary commercial steward and enterprise support provider for Jenkins, the widely used open-source continuous integration and continuous delivery automation server, and it has historically been closely associated with the Jenkins project and community. Over the years CloudBees expanded through acquisitions, including Codeship in 2018, Electric Cloud and Rollout in 2019, and ReleaseIQ in 2022, broadening its footprint from core CI/CD into release orchestration and DevSecOps capabilities. In 2025, CloudBees introduced CloudBees Unify as an early-access, AI-powered enterprise DevOps platform positioned as an operating layer that sits on top of a customer's existing toolchain, including Jenkins and Kubernetes, rather than requiring a full migration away from tools already in use. CloudBees Unify adds capabilities such as cross-platform DORA metrics and flow analytics for measuring delivery performance (lead time for changes, deployment frequency, change failure rate, and time to restore), Application Security Posture Management (ASPM), feature management, and release orchestration, along with an MCP-enabled AI foundation that CloudBees says supports automated pipeline intelligence; the company also announced a CloudBees Model Context Protocol server available through AWS Marketplace's AI Agents and Tools category in July 2025. Organizationally, CloudBees now presents its platform in three edition tiers that build on one another, with higher editions adding release orchestration, feature flags, compliance capabilities, and AI-driven test intelligence. On the financial and organizational side, CloudBees remains a privately held company; it closed a 150 million dollar Series F equity round together with a 95 million dollar debt facility, reaching a reported valuation of 1 billion dollars, with Delta-v Capital named among its investors. Despite that capital raise, CloudBees conducted layoffs in September 2025 affecting roughly 65 employees, or about 12 percent of its workforce, as part of a broader restructuring described publicly by CEO Anuj Kapur as part of investing in the company's future direction around CloudBees Unify. As of 2026, CloudBees employee counts across various data providers range from roughly 515 to 600, generally described as being in the 501-1,000 employee band. CloudBees does not publish detailed self-serve pricing; its pricing page directs prospects to request a custom quote based on team size, security requirements, and orchestration complexity, though third-party sources report a free plan for teams of up to 5 users and unverified estimates suggesting team-tier pricing in the range of 75 to 100 dollars per user per month, with enterprise pricing quoted individually based on user count, build capacity, and support requirements. CloudBees competes primarily with other enterprise CI/CD and DevOps platforms such as GitLab, GitHub Actions at the enterprise tier, Harness, and Atlassian's Bamboo, while retaining a distinct position as the company most closely tied to the Jenkins ecosystem specifically.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '4ce9a315-8686-43e9-92c6-7a9d8afd48f7';

